column168: FURX 123017 was reported to be releasing diesel fuel from the bottom of the tank car in the 18th Street Yard; Kansas City, KS.  Inspection of the car found product being released from the outboard A-end heater coil due to a loose securement cap (car equipped with interior heater coils).  The cap was tightened, stopping the release.  Investigation found the car was moving under one-time movement approval  FRA-10070458 for repair of defective heater coils.
column169: Ensure cars are properly secured prior to movement, especially when there is a known defect that has the potential to release product.

column168: Trailer 89516 was closed to Phoenix at 0340 in the AM. At some time in the early afternoon a hostler~notified me that the trailer was leaking. I traced the trailer and was unable to ascertain which of the~3 kinds of Flammable substances might be leaking , so I brought it to the dock. The substance p  ut off such~an obnoxious odor that I was forced to put the trailer back out to the yard.WE checked throughout the shift~and the odor never subsided. I contacted Roy Balentine before I left to advise him of the situation and get ~his recommendation.It was decided to leave the trailer in the yard over  night and reevaluate in the morning.~Upon unloading the trailer this morning it was determined the freight expanded due to heat and ruptured the~plastic containers and outer cardboard boxes.I have the skid of 45 ctns isolated in a trailer waiting on further instructions

column168: During a routine yard check at the ten day storage lot of the intended waste disposal facility, a van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was noticed to be leaking.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer. Two fiber drums were found to have pinhole leaks at the bottom.  The drums were overpacked into suitable salvage containers along with the spilled material and absorbents used to contain the spill, both on the trailer and on the ground.  The trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound after unloading and placed back into service.
column169: The drums leaks were evidently caused by other cargo being jammed against them causing friction to the bottom, causing the pinhole leaks.  The personnel at the origin location were to review proper blocking and bracing procedures to prevent recurrence.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column168: The drums was received at our facility in Flanders NJ with leaked material along the sides of the drum and on the floor of the pan-lined trailer.  The drum was overpacked and all leaked material was remediated.
column169: Need to check gasket condition before offering drums for shipment.

column168: A rolloff box was being offloaded at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility.  While the box was tilted in the air, approximately 10 gallons of liquid surged out of the box over the tailgate along with approximately 1/2 gallon of solid material.  The spilled material was in containment and immediately cleaned up and put back into the box.  The material had more moisture content than it was intended to.
column169: The generator was notified that the contents of the box had more moisture content than is allowed under this description.  The findings were supported by the results of the failed Paint filter test.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: During a routine yard check at the ten day storage lot of the intended waste disposal facility, a leak was noticed coming from a van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The cause was found to be a drum with a pinhole leak on the bottom--it was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the materials used to contain the spill along with the material which had leaked onto the ground.  The trailer was then taken to the intended waste disposal facility where it was unloaded. The trailer was cleaned with a cleaning compound and placed back into service.
column169: The pinhole leak in the drum was caused by corrosion on the underneath side.  The drum was old and used. The driver checked the drum for leaks at time of pickup and found none.  The generator was notified of the incident and advised to use caution when using used drums for transporting shipments.

column168: CN mechanical department employee noted a small amount product dripping from the bottom outlet valve of tank car PLCX 129272(L / ALCOHOLS, N.O.S.) during an inspection at the CN Fond du Lac Yard, North Fond du Lac, WI. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. Shipper's Response Contractor noted product leaking from between the bottom outlet valve and the tank car body. Attempt was made to tighten the bottom outlet flange bolts. The leak was slowed but not stopped. Containment was placed under valve assembly and monitored. Product was transferred into UTLX 207353 on 08/05/2010. Shipper to seek movement approval for PLCX 129272.

column168: Car was reported to be leaking from the manway opening.  Inspection of the car revealed 2 of 6 manway swingbolts in position, not wrench tight. column168: While at the UPRR Livonia, LA yard, an odor was detected coming from an unknown location on the tank car.  The car was isolated without incident or injury and Hulcher Professional Service, a contractor, was dispatched by UPRR Haz Mat Mgr T. M. Robinson. Robinson also contacted the consignee, Terra Nitrogen and they dispatched a technician. Inspection revealed a slight vapor release form the left quadrant of the pressure plate. Using a torque multiplier wrench, the contractor was able to tighten 12 of 22 bolts on the pressure plate and this secured the car from leaking.
column169: All cars on fleet need inspection for proer torque of pressure plate bolts.

column168: On 08/02/2010 at 07:45 hrs., personnel in the CSXT North Bergen Yard, in North Bergen, NJ, discovered car TILX 400927, a loaded tank car of CO2 Carbon Dioxide, venting from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Linde LLC, local, state and federal agencies were notified. CHEMTREC Report # 2010080200030. React Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disk had ruptured. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (John Mack 908-329-9300).  React Environmental stood by until car depressurized and the shipper replaced the frangible disk. The leak was secured and the car was placed on a stub track to build pressure and will be moved on to destination.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  A WA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI Code: 2 (5+1+0) x (3+0) = 36

column168: On 08/09/2010 at 00:35 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Tilford yard, in Atlanta, GA, discovered SHPX 205240, a loaded tank car of Methanol, leaking vapor from the manway area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Methanex Methanol Company, local emergency responders, and Chemtrec were notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2010-08-09-00008). Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found four of the eight manway bolts less than tool tight. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative, George Wellon (cell 214-415-9325). Eagle/ SWS secured the manway. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI code: 5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: Hazardous Materials Manager Chris Machenberg spoke with George Wellon of Methanex Methanol Company about this incident. Mr. Machenberg was informed that additional training was being performed at the loading location in Wilmington, North Carolina.

column168: This shipment was delivered to the UPS Air Freight Service Center in SHV as a non-hazmat.  U.S. Customs opened the package to clear it, thinking it was an import shipment, when in reality, it was an export.  It was at this time that it was realized that this was a hazardous materials shipment.  There were no markings/labels, etc., nothing on the outer package that would lead anyone to believe that this was a hazardous materials shipment.  Additionally, the shipping papers (Air Waybill/Shipper's Letter of Instruction) did not contain any references that this was a Hazardous Materials shipment.  In fact, the AWB/SLI states that this is not a hazardous materials shipment.
column169: Recommend that this shipper ensure that their shipping employees are re-trained in Hazardous Materials recognition and proper shipping procedures IAW U.S. 49CFR/ICAO/IATA.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported product expelled from the manway closure of GATX 200607 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) during switching operations in the railyard.  Movement of GATX 200607 was stopped. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 200607 and reported finding two manway securement bolts less than tool tight. The responder loosened and then properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts in the required pattern to ensure a good tight closure. Intact manway seal Abengoa Bioenergy 044813 was replaced with BNSF seal numbered 001258. Spillage on the side shell evaporated and no ground impact was observed. No further product release was observed during subsequent movements of GATX 200607 in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver was preparing to unload product at consignee location when hydrochloric acid vapors were noted emanating from the trailer door.  The driver donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The driver found the source of the vapors.  The 2” bung was found to be dislodged from the 10" cap and a small amount of product had leaked onto the top of the tote.  No material leaked onto the trailer floor.  The driver tightened the bung and cleaned the spilled material.  When the vapors in the trailer had dissipated, the delivery was completed.
column169: Although no vapors were noted during loading or in the driver's pre-trip inspection, we surmize that the bung in the cap was not fully tightenend and worked free during the transportation phase resulting in the vapor release and minor leak.  Employees complete a checklist when filling containers that includes examining closures.  All employees will be informed of this incident and retrained on IBC inspection with a focus on checking the bungs in the caps.

column168: Our driver loaded sulfuric acid at General Chemical.  Around 1700 on August 11,2010, he pulled out onto the street and went up hill on N.Texas Road acid spilled out the back of the dome onto the street.  He had not realized that the dome was not tightened down secure enough.  The driver stopped on the hill and did a quick equipment check.  The driver did not notice the spill at the time, and drove away.  Around 2200 on August 11, 2010, I received a call from Mark Kresovsky notifying me of the spill.  General Chemical personnel cleaned up the spill and we talked again around August 12,2010 at 0045.  The spill was contained and we would follow up the next morning.  NRC Evironmental Services came out the General Chemical around August 12, 2010 to finish the road clean up.  I met with Brian Hanson at General Chemical at 1615; NRC was still there completing the clean up.
column169: Working with General Chemical, we are instituting a new procedure where the loader makes the driver go back up on top of the traile and double-check the dome before leaving their property.  We are also encouraging all of our drivers to make sure and take the time to double-check their domes before leaving any loading facility.

column168: On August 12, 2010 at 12:27 FRA HazMat Inspector Joel Roberts reported to CSX Transportation that he noted an odor about tank car GATX 5208. GATX 5208 had been offered to CSX Transportation in CN Rail train M38331-11. Tank was a load of Ammonia Solution, Class 8, UN2672, PG III.CSXT notified CN Rail and the shipper via Chemtrec, report number 2010-08-12-00157.CSX dispatched SWS/Eagle ER Group out of Findlay, OH to respond. At 14:38 August 12, 2010 Mr. John Siefert, Division Manager for SWS/Eagle advised CSX that the source of the leak was from around the threads of the vacuum relief valve. The device was removed and putty put on threads then replaced. Leak was secured.

column168: A Texas DOT rail inspector reported to BNSF that NATX 29722 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was observed dripping product from its bottom outlet valve's closure cap (BOV-BOC). A receptacle was placed under the BOV to catch drips. A BNSF contractor inspected NATX 29722 and reported that the BOV was in the closed position. The BOV was worked (open/closed) in an attempt to clear the valve seat of any contaminates. The BOC was loosened to inspect the BOC gasket condition. Once the BOC was loosened, product sprayed from its threaded connection into the receptacle under the BOV. The BOC was then tool tightened, stopping further product drips by 1100 hrs. CDT, 8/10/2010. The BOV was presumed faulty, as it was allowing product to by-pass this closed valve. NATX 29722 was monitored and no further product drips from the BOC were observed. Captured spillage evaporated. The shipper requested and was granted FRA-10080489 movement authority to redirect NATX 29722 back to its loading origin for product off-loading, thence to a qualified repair facility for BOV repairs. No further incidents were reported on the BNSF during pre-trip and return transit of NATX 29722.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was parked at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility. The trailer then was unloaded at the intended waste disposal facility without incident.
column169: When the tote was loaded into the trailer, the cap was checked by two individuals who both stated that it was secured.  After unloading, the tote was taken out of service and carefully examined.  The closure was found to be defective and the tote was taken out of service.

column168: A BNSF switchman in the railyard reported SHPX 221937 (DOT 112J340W tank car) emanating a product odor. SHPX 221937 was cordoned-off in the railyard. The consignee (Koch Nitrogen Company) was notified and contract responders inspected SHPX 221937. The responders reported a vapor hiss from the vapor valve's closure plug. The vapor valve was approximately 1/8 turn from being fully closed and its closure plug was only hand tight. Responders fully closed the vapor valve and its closure plug was tool tightened, ending the residue product vapor hiss and associated product odor. Other valves were inspected for securement and the two liquid valves were also found partially open with their closure plugs not tool tight. The responders closed the liquid valves and tool tightened the closure plugs. Response was concluded by 0950 hrs. CDT, 8/16/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A Truck tractor-Semi trailer-Full trailer from FedEX was transporting 4 drums of varnish (Class 3, Paint Related Material UN 1263) when one of the drums split, in 4 places, and began to leak out the contents. As the material flowed to the rear of the rear most trailer, it spilled out the bottom right corner and splashed upon another CMV as it was passed by the FedEX CMV. The second CMV driver then passed the FedEX CMV and motioned for him to pull to the shoulder. (The damage to the second CMV included varnish of the front and sides of the truck tractor and on the windshield).The Marshall Fire Department and the Illinois State Police were contacted and the right lane of I70 near Milepost 144 was closed off to traffic. Upon my arrival, I found the material leaking at a rate of approximately 1 gallon per minute. The material had leaked through the front of the trailer but most of the material was leaking at the rear right side of the trailer. The trailer was disconnected from the other units and the fire department had a water line at the ready. Westbound traffic was moved over to the far left shoulder and allowed to continue. A Haz Mat cleanup crew was arranged for by the carrier and as we waited for their arrival, the temperature of the trailer show 118 degrees Fat the lower right front corner of the trailer. The pavement under the trailer showed a temperature of 125 degrees F. Upon the arrival of the Haz Mat crew, the spilled material on the ground was neutralized with dry powder. Dry powder was also used to neutralize the spilled material in the trailer. According to Matt SMITH (Spill Recover Of Indiana), one of the four 55 gal drums split at the bottom. The trailer was relocated to a Fed EX lot in Effingham, IL where the spill was cleaned up. Photos of the trailer and drum damage were taken by Mr. SMITH.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

Release only last about 15 minutes until the salvage drum was in place.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was to be unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into other trailer destined for various intended waste disposal facilities.  Upon opening the rear door of the trailer, a shipment of fluorescent bulbs was found to have 1 box which had been crushed by other boxes which had moved into it.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and swept up the broken bulbs, placing the contents into an appropriate salvage container.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.

column168: UTLX 207490 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported in the railyard with fresh product on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 207490 finding the leak source at the manway closure. The shipper seal on the manway closure was intact. The manway had 4 of 6 securement bolts that were not tool tight with the other two not applied. The manway gasket was inspected and found serviceable. The manway gasket was wiped clean and returned. The manway lid was then closed and all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened. Securement response was concluded by 0310 hrs. CDT, 8/7/2010. Afterwards, UTLX 207490 was moved to a location in the railyard so that product spillage on the tank shell could be cleaned.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: On 08/10/2010 at 13:04 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Export Yard, in Jacksonville, FL,  discovered TAEX 780, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from top of car. The car was isolated and the shipper, The Andersons Incorporated, was contacted via Chemtrec (Report number 2010-08-10-00184).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line valve in the open position and the closure plug less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Shawn Sachs at 574-596-4973. Eagle/SWS closed the liquid line valve and tightened the plug with a wrench.  The car was decontaminated and released to destination.      This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Nonconformance Report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 119  5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = NARRI 80
column169: Meet with operators and review proper procedures for securing tank cars.

column168: Vehicle hit a 200-250 pound wild boar on Texas Hwy 14 approximately one mile south of Thornton, TX.  Vehicle ran off the highway, flipped and caught fire. Driver had severe injuries and was airlifted to Parkland Hospital, Dallas, TX where she expired.  Three Mo-99 return generators were on board: 41.65 GBq, Tl 0.2; 16.04 GBq, Tl 0.1; and 10.5 GBq, Tl 0.1.  Each Mo-99 generator contained 40 pounds depleted uranium shielding.  All three packages were unaffected by the fire, remained intact and were not damaged.  There was no release of material; no potential release of material; no contamination; and no excessive exposure. The three generators are being picked up from the Texas Highway Patrol by Associated Couriers, Inc.  This report is filed pursuant to 49 CFR 171.15(b)(2).

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported product odor emanating from a group of tank cars that they had just switched into a yard track in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and inspected these tank cars during daylight. Responder's inspection revealed that GATX 68560 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) had a product trail on the top shell emanating from this tank car's manway closure. A piece of a manway gasket was found stuck atop the tank shell near than manway nozzle. The shipper seal on the manway cover (Valero Inc 081545) was intact. Responder found 4 of 6 manway securement bolts less than tool tight. Inspection of the manway gasket condition revealed no manway gasket in place. The responder applied a new manway gasket and properly tool tightened all six manway securement bolts. Spillage on the shell of GATX 68560 had cooled and hardened. No ground impact from spillage was observed. Another identical shipment in tank car GATX 68572 nearby was inspected and also found with 4 of 6 manway securement bolts less than tool tight. The responder tool tightened these loose manway securement bolts. No product release from GATX 68572 was observed. Response was concluded by 1010 hrs. CDT, 8/25/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

On 8/15/2010 at 16:37 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Selkirk Yard, in Selkirk, NY, discovered GATX 58033, a loaded tank car of Waste Caustic Alkali Liquid, N.O.S., had leaked from the top and had residue streaks of product on the sides of the tank car. Irving Oil Refining GP was notified along with Albany County EMA, New York State DEC and CHEMTREC (Report 2010-08-15-00043). EP+S of Vermont, a CSXT emergency contractor was dispatched and found the manway nozzle gasket had a 3 inch tear in the center rib of the gasket, allowing product to seep out. The issue was identified and the nozzle gasket was replaced. Corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative (Nick Milutin 713-823-1780). The car was decontaminated, secured and inspected for leaks then  released for disposition.    An AAR Q+A 7.1 form was not required for this incident.  This incident did require a special move.    Cause Code: 209  NARRI Code: 5 (5+5+1) x (2+0) = 110

column168: DRIVER WAS ASKED BY COMPANY OFFICIALS TO PULL A SAMPLE OF STYRENE FOR ANALYSIS.  DRIVER OPENED THE INTERNAL VALVE, OPENED THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND REMOVED THE DUST COVER.  THE PRODUCT BEGAN FLOWING AT A HIGH RATE.  DRIVER HIT THE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF FOR THE INTERNAL VALVE; PRODUCT CONTINUED TO FLOW.  HE CLOSED OFF THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND THE FLOW STOPPED.  APPROXIMATELY 110 GALLONS OF STYRENE WAS LOST.  THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE SURROUNDING AREA.  THE SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TESTED WITH NO CONTAMINATION PRESENT.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A FOREIGN OBJECT, A BROKEN BOLT AND NUT HAD LODGED BETWEEN THE VALVE AND DISCHARGE OUTLET PREVENTING THE INTERNAL VALVE FROM SEALING SHUT.
column169: DRIVER FAILED TO FOLLOW PROCEDURE.  THE DUST CAP SHOULD HAVE BEEN OPENED FIRST, PRIOR TO ANY VALVES BEING OPENED.  EVEN THOUGH THE INTERNAL VALVE FAILED TO SEAL, IF PROPER PROCEDURE HAD BEEN FOLLOWED, THE SPILL COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED. MARTIN WILL MAKE SURE DRIVERS ARE TRAINED IN PROPER PROCEDURE FOR OPENING AND CLOSING VALVES AND DUSTCAPS.

column168: On 8-06-2010, around 545am Univar material handler hooked up a 2" hose female end to a railcar of sodium hydroxide.  The railcar was pressurized and the product valve was opened to fill Univar sodium hydroxide tanks.  While transloading, a Univar approved carrier arrived around 6am to load for a customer needing sodium hydroxide.  The tanker was backed into position and handlers began loading the tanker.   While transloading into the tanker, a handler noticed product squirting out of the 2" female hose cam ears. This hose was attached to railcar.  At this point the railcar product valve was shut and they closed all connections from the railcar.   After cleaning up the 100 gallons of sodium hydroxide we disconnected the hose that was attached to the railcar and attached to Univar railstand and found no 2" gasket was in the female end of the hose. This allowed sodium hydroxide to squirt out the cam ears of Univar hose. After reviewing the incident with Safety Committee, it was determined the gasket missing from the 2" hose was the reason the product was release out of hose cam ears.       All material was pumped out of the rail line and drain blocks were put down in case we had any more material release from railcar.  Univar OM is self contained with gate valve on property.  At no time did sodium hydroxide get into the sewer system and all sodium hydroxide was pumped into disposable tote.
column169: Bulk handlers who will deal with connecting, disconnecting, loading and transferring of railcars or tankers will need to connect equipment and 2nd handler will need to verify connections are complete and no issues with any area of the hoses, railcar or tank truck.    September meeting we will retrain material handlers on tank truck load and unload basics along with rail tank car unloading basics.

column168: MATERIAL HAD BEEN PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT FOR A FARMER.  FARMER LEFT W/THE NURSE TANK AROUND 3:50PM ON 8-10-2010 & AROUND 4:15P.M. THE FARMER CALLED THE OFFICE TO REPORT THAT HE HAD ROLLED THE TANK INTO A BAR DITCH ON HWY 77 SOUTH OF ORLANDO Y AT THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 77 & 164.  HE REPORTED THAT NO PRODUCT WAS COMING FROM THE TANK AT THAT POINT.  WE CALLED A TOW TRUCK AND GOT THE TANK BACK TO PERRY AROUND 4:00 P.M. AND LEFT FOR THE NIGHT.  AT AROUND 9:00P.M. WE RECEIVED A CALL THAT THE NURSE TANK WAS LEAKING SO WE CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND GOT THE RELEASE STOPPED AROUND 9:45 P.M. ON 8-11-10 WE TOOK THE TANK TO A REMOTE LOCATION AND TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED TANK TO A SECURE TANK WITHOUT RELEASING ANY MORE PRODUCT.
column169: MAKE SURE FARMERS UNDERSTAND WHAT THE PROPER TOWING SPEED IS FOR OUR NURSE TANKS BEFORE THEY LEAVE THE PROPERTY.  WE CAN ALSO DO A BETTER JOB OF CHECKING SAFETY CHAINS, HITCHES, WHEELS, TIRES AND RUNNING GEAR BEFORE SENDING EACH TANK OUT.

column169: USE SKIDS TO PROTECT BETTER.  PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. WHEN  LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OR LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON THE TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: The shipment was discovered leaking during the sort.  The bottle of undeclared Resin Solution was offered in FedEx Pak. The FAA was notified; I left a voicemail for Division Manager Janet McLaughlin in Washington, DC.  The CAA in Japan will also be notified.

column168: A J.B. Hunt driver notified BNSF in-gate personnel that intermodal container JBHU 239625 (recently delivered to the BNSF intermodal facility) was leaking an unknown liquid substance. JBHU 239625 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area. BNSF contract responders inspected the lading inside JBHU 239625 finding a 30 gallon poly drum loaded atop a wooden pallet toward the container's nose was leaking contents. Closer inspection revealed that two protruding pallet nails rubbed against the drum's bottom causing abrasion holes allowing product to leak out. Responders overpacked this leaking drum and placed absorbant materials on the floor spillage inside JBHU 239625. Afterwards, all spillage was diluted and removed. Spillage on the outside of JBHU 239625 and on the J.B. Hunt's tractor was diluted and cleaned. The contents of the overpack drum was profiled for appropriate disposal.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: While this tank car was being switched at the KCS West Lake Rose Bluff yard, it was discovered that GATX 2017, load, Hydrochloric Acid, was found leaking from the rupture disk. The car released liquid lading only when moved and caused a small visible vapor cloud.  The car was isolated to prevent further movement and a isolation zone was established around the container. KCS-CID notified the LA State Police per regulatory requirement.  Also, KCS-CID notified Chemtrec for shipper notification. The consignee responded to the incident and assisted with decon and rupture disk replacement.       Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated. This estimated quantity was required because the shippers only provided bulk quantities on shipping paper, as "1 Tank Car", per DOT requirements.  Carrier is not provided specific quantity information as required by DOT to facilitate this report electronically via the Release Reporter.. This action required by preparer to facilitate data acceptance by defective DOT IT system edits.    KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 will apply
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.

column168: On 08/24/2010 at 15:33 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Siebert yard, Mobile, Alabama, discovered GLNX 34629, a loaded tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking from the dome area of the car. The car was isolated and workers were sheltered in place. The shipper, Transammonia, Inc., Chemtrec, NRC and local emergency responders were notified via Chemtrec, #2010-08-24-00241. USES, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor leak from the pressure relief device, (PRD). The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Angie King  813-546-2237. USES replaced the retaining cap and both o-rings which stopped the leak. The leak was secured and the car released for transport pending an FRA movement approval. This incident resulted in the CSX mainline tracks being shut down for approximately four hours and stopped switching activities at the North end of the terminal for approximately four hours.     This incident did require a switching move.  This incident requires a Q+A 7.1 Nonconformance Report    Cause Code: 414  NARRI code: 2(5+9+2) X (2+0) = 64
column169: Contacted Angie King of Transammonia and sugguested to have a safety advisory issued by Transammonia and have the companies that the cars are leased from perform and audit on the Pressure Relief Valves to check the condition and compatablity of the o-rings.

column168: WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 49 NORTHBOUND, PULLING A LOADED MC 307 TANKER CONTAINING A "FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1993, NOS (METHANOL) MR. DONALD WALKER CHOKED ON HIS ICE TEA, ATTEMPTED TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE, AND PASSED OUT.  HE LEFT THE ROADWAY, AND ROLLED ONTO HIS RIGHT SIDE.  THE CRACH CAUSE A LEAK FROM TWO OF THE WASH OUT CAPS.  THE LEAKES WERE CONTAINED BY THE TOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE ESTIMATED LEAKAGE WAS CALCULATED TO BE LESS THAN 35 GALLONS.  NO PRODUCT WAS INTRODUCED TO ANY WATER SUPPLY OR RIVER.  THE RESPONDER INCLUDED LOCAL POLICE, EMS, FIRE DEPARTMENTS, STATE POLICE, THE STATE DEQ, A CONTRACT RESPONDER (OIL MOP OF LOUSISANA), A SAFEWAY TANKER AND DRIVER, AND A CLEAN UP AND RECOVERY CONTRACT CREW FROM OIL MAP OF LOUISIANA.  A COMMAND CENTER WAS SETUP BY THE LOCAL POLICE DEPARTMENT.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND EXCAUATED AND PLACED IN TWO 55 GALLON CONTAINERS.  THE RECOVERY AND CLEAN UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED, AND THE TRACTOR & TRAILER WERE TOWED TO A LOCAL WRECKER YARD.  A SEVEN DAY "UNAUTHORIZED DISCHARGE REPORT WAS SENT TO THE LOUISIANA DEQ ON 8/16/10.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED BY SAFEWAY AND A SPILL CENTER CONTROL # WAS ISSUED. (951967). THIS REPORT IS BEING PRESENTED BECAUSE OF THE BLOCKAGE OF A MAJOR HIGHWAY FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 HOURS.  THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENTS THE SAFEWAY DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL AND RELEASED THAT EVENING.
column169: MR. DONALD WALKER FAILED TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE.  HE CHOKED ON A DRINK OF ICE TEA. HE SAID HE PASSED OUT AND WHEN HE CAM TO HE WAS HANGING UPSIDE DOWN BY HIS SEAT BELT.  HE ALSO CLAIMS TO HAVE HAD A RECENT HISTORY OF CHOKING.  HE DID NOT REVEAL THIS TO ANYONE IN SAFEWAY.  TYPICALLY A GROWN PERSON WOULD CONTROL HIMSELF AND WATCH HOW HE DRINK SOMETHING, IF HE HAD A CHOKING PROBLEM.  OBVIOUSLY, HE COULD NOT DO SO.  IN THE END HE FAILED TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF A TRACTOR AND TRAILER WEIGHING 80,00 LBS.  1. A COST CAUSE ANALYSIS WILL BE CONDUCTED BY THE COMPANY.  2. A LETTER WILL BE SEND TO THE FIELD ADVISING DRIVERS TO REFRAIN FROM EATING OR DRINKING IN THEIR TRUCKS IF THEY HAVE A PROBLEM WITH CHOKING.  THEY SHOULD ALLSO ADVISE THEIR DISPATCH OF ANY PECULIAR ILLNESS OR INJURY, SO THAT PRECAUTIONS CAN BE TAKEN.  3. (THE DRIVER WILL BE DISMISSED BY THE COMPANY).

column168: A Texas DOT rail safety inspector reported to BNSF that NATX 16168 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was observed in the railyard dripping product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected NATX 16168 finding product trail evidence that the BOV flange plate connection to the tank car (belly flange) was the leak source. The responder tool tightened one mounting flange hex bolt approximately 3/4 turn and also the two hex bolts adjacent on either side slightly. Afterwards, no further product drips were observed. All shipper seals were intact and all other valves/fittings were found secure. The dried crystallized product residue on the underside of NATX 16168 was diluted with neutralizing solution. Response was concluded by 1530 hrs. CDT, 8/30/2010.   The side specification stencil on NATX 16168 indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005 and next due in 2015.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The Captain on the Horizon Challenger reported a small leak from container HRZU434310 which was loaded with 38 Residue, Last Contained Empty Totes, UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid, 8, PGII.  The leak was managed since it was small totaling about two gallons over the five days that the vessel was in transit.  A response crew boarded the vessel upon arrival and prepared to receive the container on the terminal.  The cart was lined with plastic to ensure that there was not leakage.  The totes have a metal frame and a metal bottom.  The shipped is still investigating the leak but believe that it was caused by a metal grounding screw in the bottom of the tote close to the discharge valve.  It is believed that the screw was affected by the acid.
column169: Only plastic packaging should be provided for any part of an IBC that is to come into contact with a corrosive agent.  The shipper was unsure why the supplier provided totes with the screw in the bottom.

column168: CPDX 202078 (AAR 211A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported with fresh product on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected CPDX 202078. No ground impact from the spillage was observed. The shipper seal at the manway closure of CPDX 202078 was intact, but all six manway securement bolts were found to be hand tight only. The manway gasket condition was not inspected at this time. The responder properly secured all six manway securement bolts prior to 1850 hrs. CDT, 8/27/2010. Afterwards, CPDX 202078 was moved to an isolated track location for BNSF contractors to clean the spillage off CPDX 202078's shell.  CPDX 202078's tank shell was cleaned on 8/30/2010 without further incident.  Two other identical shipments nearby were also inspected. Tank car SRIX 81096 had all six manway securement bolts less than tool tight; and tank car GLNX 23038 had all eight manway securement bolts less than tool tight. The responder properly tool tightened the manway securement bolts on both SRIX 81096 and GLNX 23038.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A strong chemical odor (akin to odorized petroleum gas) was reported at the south end of the railyard. Switching operations were suspended while investigation into the odor source continued. GATX 53294 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was identified as the odor source. GATX 53294 was isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection by BNSF contract responders. The responders reported that inspection of the manway securement revealed that the manway gasket was misaligned with all the manway securement bolts tight.  The responders replaced the misaligned gasket with a new suitable manway gasket; and resecured the manway closure. The responders noted that the manway cover may be 'warped' as they had difficulty ensuring all manway securement bolts maintained a tool tight condition with manway gasket integrity during the final closure securement process. New seals applied to the manway closure and valve housing cover were seals numbered BNSF 2877009 and 2877001 respectively.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The emergency response contractor was handling a spill on the Horizon Challenger for the same shipper.  As the vessel was being unloaded with containers, the longshore removed the hatch cover from the vessel and discovered HRZU434310 leaking on top of another container.  The vessel unloading operations were stopped until the response contractor could attend to the spill that was on the vessel in the hole of the ship.  This required removing and reworking the leaking container along with neutralizing and cleaning the container below it as well as the vessel hole as well.  The product leaking was UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid, 8 PGII that was in 38 Residue, Last Contained Empty Totes.  The USCG was present and contacted PHMSA.  The unloading and reworking of the containers took place under the view of the USCG and PHMSA.  The composite totes had a metal frame around the plastic container.  The metal plate on the bottom of the tote prevented the contractor or anyone from making a firm determination as to the cause of the leak.      The consignee advised that it is suspected that the tote manufacturer has a metal grounding screw behind the valve inside the tote and that the screw was compromised by the acid.  All the acid was vaccumed, neutralized and washed down with the contents slated for compliant disposal.    were present during the unloading operations

column168: On August 9, 2010, at approximately 12:15 a.m. CST, a Z&K Fuel Transport tractor-tanker experienced a mechanical failure. The failure was at the fifth wheel connection between the tractor and the tanker. This failure resulted in the tanker separating from the tractor. The right side of the front end of the tanker sustained a six inch gash after the tanker separated from the tractor unit. Approximately 1,962 gallons of gasoline were released from the tanker and spilled onto soil and an asphalt parking lot. The Summit and Forest View Fire Departments, in cooperation with the Metropolitan Water Reclamation District of Greater Chicago (MWRD), then diluted and washed the gasoline down a nearby storm drain which connects to the MWRD sewage treatment plant. The tanker involved in the incident contained approximately 8,404 gallons of product. A product recovery tanker was provided by Klemm Tank Lines and dispatched to the site. Approximately 6,442 gallons of product was transferred from the Z&K fuel Transport tanker into the recovery tanker provided by Klemm Tank Lines. Bills of lading were utilized to determine the approximate 1,962 gallons of product which was released from the tanker due to the incident.     On August 9,2010, at approximately 1000 CST Z&K Fuel Transport contacted HazChem in order to perform emergency response and remediation activities on its behalf of Z&K Fuel Transport. At approximately 1144 CST, Z&K Fuel Transport contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) to manage and oversee environmental operations on Z&K Fuel Transport's behalf.     Pursuant to Illinois State regulations, ERTS notified the Illinois Emergency Management Agency. The IEMA issued report number H2O10-0872 to this report. IEMA was also notified by Summit Fire Department and report number H2010-0868. The National Response Center (NRC) was notified of the incident as well.  NRC assigned incident report number 950328 to the incident. The Metropolitan Water Reclamation District of Greater Chicago (MWRD) was notified of the incident and a report number was not available at the time of this report.     On August 9, 2010, HazChem arrived on site and worked in conjunction with Environmental Protection Agency (IEPA) personnel to secure and contain the site. HazChem personnel utilized a vacuum truck to collect a mixture foam, water, and gasoline which had accumulated in local sewer lines due to emergency response efforts of local fire departments. Approximately 300 gallons of contaminated liquid were removed from the sewer lines. Granular absorbent was utilized along with street sweeper equipment in order to collect the released materials from the asphalt parking lot. The area of asphalt parking lot measured approximately 150' by 100'.  All granular absorbent material was containerized for transportation and proper disposal.     Additional response measures were pursued by HazChem personnel to an area of soil immediately adjacent to the parking lot. HazChem pe
column169: • The subject fifth wheel is a JOST model number JSK37VSLB7PG12, herein referred to as the “fifth wheel”.    • The fifth wheel has gouge marks on its top face consistent with a trailer kingpin separation and subsequent detachment.  The trailer glad-hand and power connection have damage to them consistent with an unintended trailer separation.  The tractor rear axle outer dually tire has a puncture and tread damage consistent with being impacted by the trailer after the separation.      • The trailer tires are all intact.    • The fifth wheel was acuated with a JOST test kingpin and the lock-bar did not fully engage.  Further the handle lock did not engage.  The test kingpin was loose in the fifth wheel due to the failure of the lock-bar and handle lock to engage.     • The fifth wheel was used to connect to an actual trailer kingpin and the same locking failure was seen.    • The observed fifth wheel locking mechanism abnormality is consistent with the trailer separation incident that occurred on 8/9/10 at Rt. 171 and Archer Ave.      • The specific cause of the fifth wheel locking mechanism abnormality is currently under investigation by SEA Project Engineer David Stobbe, P.E., IL License No. 062061985.

column168: HOKX 8283 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) in the railyard was reported leaking product from the bottom of this tank car near the sump area. HOKX 8283 was isolated in the railyard with containment placed under it. Contract responders applied lime to neutralize product impacted ground areas, and later excavated impacted ground gravel.  Excavated material was profiled for final disposal. Arrangements for transferring remaining product from HOKX 8283 to another suitable tank car (HOKX 8338) were finalized. Product transfer was completed without incident by 1500 hrs. CDT, 8/09/2010. Afterwards, the interior of HOKX 8283 was neutralized and cleaned of product residue with a water/soda ash solution. A liner failure near the welded sump area at the bottom end of the liquid eduction dip tube was suspected as the cause of the tank corrosion hole. FRA-10080520 movement approval received to forward HOKX 8283 to a qualified repair facility.  HOKX 8283's specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005 and next due in 2015; lining applied 05/1995 and spark tested 10/2005.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman reported that after completing an air test on GATX 23423 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) at the repair track, he experienced dizziness with a headache from product fumes emanating from GATX 23423. GATX 23423 was cordoned-off. The BNSF employee was taken to a local hospital for examination and treatment for chemical inhalation exposure. The employee was examined, provided oxygen and aspirin; and released without further treatment. BNSF and contract responders inspected GATX 23423 finding all valves and fittings secure, but evidence of product leaking from the manway closure was observed. It was concluded that the manway gasket was the cause of the product release since all the manway securement bolts were tool tight. The shipper was notified and sent responders to assess the condition of GATX 23423. The shipper responders initiated air monitoring procedures findings no recordable readings at or atop GATX 23423. The manway was opened and responders reported that the manway gasket was missing. The product outage was deemed appropriate. The responders installed a new manway gasket and resecured the manway cover prior to 1013 hrs. MDT, 8/19/2010. GATX 23423 was then scheduled to return to the shipper to clean the dried spillage off its tank shell.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings, including all securement components are applied correctly and in place.

column168: Driver  hooked up to 07, did his pre-trip inspection, Driver left the branch and drove to Darigold in Issaquah, WA, where he began unloading the AC105 out of compartments 1 and 4, while unloading the AC-105, Driver noticed AC-55-5 Red leaking out of the drain tube on the tanker, he noticed the spill was coming from the top of the tanker. He placed a bucket under the spill, then climbed to the top of the tanker and noticed the leak was coming from the threads on the pressure relief valve of compartment 2. Driver bled the pressure off the compartment, when there was no pressure the leak stopped and Driver tightened the entire pressure relief valve assembly ¼ turn. Less than 1 liter of product had leaked unto the ground, Driver notified Darigold receiver Lorenzo. Driver and receiver removed product from ground using absorbent pads till pavement was dry. No product reached the drain. Driver contacted Supervisor Jeunene Petitte via phone call at time of incident.  When ready to unload compartment, he ran the customers airline to the trailer, hooked it up and unloaded the compartment into customer’s tank. The product did not leak after tightening the pressure relief valve. It was found that the material handler while loading the tanker, had removed the pressure relief valve to connect a fitting on the tanker for top loading. When replacing the pressure relief valve, it was hand tightened. Also, the tanker volumetrically appeared to be overloaded, causing the product to drip from threads of pressure relief valve.
column169: New couplers will added to the blind flanges of tanker 07 to attach top load fittings. Pressure relief valve will no longer be removed.  Material handlers will be trained regarding the 49CFR 173.24(h), 173.24b (a) (1), (2), 173.24b(c) (2) outage requirements.    Spanner wrenches will be ordered to carry on all tankers for tightening of any loose devices.

column168: ON 8/29/10, AT ABOUT 3:30 AM, OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON I10, AT MILE MARKER 834, NEAR HAMPSHIRE, TX. HE WAS APPROACHING A VEHICEL AHEAD OF HIM AND NOTICED THAT HE WAS GETTING NEAR THE VEHICLE, SO HE BEGAN TO SWITCH LANES. WHILE SWITCHING LANES HE NOTICED THAT A VEHICLE ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY WAS COMING TOWARDS HIM. THE DRIVER TOOK CORRECTIVE ACTION AND BY DOING SO HE CLIPPED THE VEHICLE IN THE RIGHT HAND LANE AND ROLLED OVER. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET OUT OF THE TRUCK AND BEGAN TO STOP THE VEHICLES ON THE HIGHWAY AND CHECKED ON THE OCCUPANTS OF THE OTHER VEHICLE. HE NOTICED THAT HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING, SO CALLED THE TEXAS DEPT. OF PUBLIC SAFETY AND REPORTED THE ACCIDENT. WHEN THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER THE STREET SIDE OF THE TRAILER HIT THE PAVEMENT AND IT DEVELOPED A 1 1.2 INCH CRACK ON THE SEEM WELD ATTACHING THE FRONT HEAD OF THE TRAILER. IT WAS ABOVE THE SADDLE PORTION THAT HOLDS THE BODY. THE TRAILER BEGAN TO RELEASE VAPORS AND VENTED FOR ABOUT 12 HOURS. AFTER THE PRESSURE WENT DOWN ON THE TRAILER A PATCH WAS PUT OVER THE CRACK AND ABOUT 7% IF THE PRODUCT WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER. A FLARE WAS THEN ATTACHED TO THE TRAILER AND THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT WAS FLARED OFF. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS THEN RAISED AND THEN CARRIED TO AWAY. AFTER RAISING THE TRUCK, IT WAS FOUND THAT ABOUT 8 GALLONS OF MOTOR OIL HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND. TEXAS DEQ WAS NOTIFIED AND APPROPRIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO CLEAN AREA.
column169: EMPHASIS ON DEFENSIVE DRIVING WILL BE ADMINISTERED.

column168: A four compartment covered hopper, UNPX 120334 (AAR C113 car kind) was reported leaking product from a center bottom outlet, leaving a product trail from the hump crest through a group retarder to the bowl tracks in the railyard. UNPX 120334 was cordoned-off during assessment by BNSF mechanical and operating responders. Apparently, the hopper #3 outlet's locking device (elbow hinged style) vibrated to a non-locking position which allowed product to escape from the bottom outlet. Also noted was that the support bar for the hopper #3 outlet was bent. This support bar defect appeared to be old damage. The bend in the support bar may have contributed to the hopper outlet #3's door hinge locking device from staying in the secured locked position. BNSF mechanical responders were able to close the outlet, relock and secure UNPX 120334's hopper outlet #3's locking device. A contractor vacuumed all visible ground spillage. The captured spillage along with ballast and other ground debris were placed and held in roll-off containers for the shipper's salvage/disposal process implementation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 8/21/2010 at 10:02 hrs., the CSXT car department personnel at Selkirk Yard, in Selkirk, NY, discovered UTLX 200863, a residue tank car last containing Alcohols N.O.S., dripping from the bottom outlet valve 4 securement cap. The shipper, East Coast Refueling, LLC, was notified via Chemtrec, #20100821-00050. Miller Environmental Group responded and found the bottom outlet valve handle not pinned in place and partly open, and the 4 bottom outlet cap to be less than tool tight. Miller personnel tightened the bottom outlet cap, closed the valve handle, and secured the handle pin in place. The car was then released for disposition.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause code: 662  NARRI code: 5 (1+3+0) x (2+0) = 40
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Human Error
column168: On 08/24/2010 at 11:01 hrs., a conductor at the CSXT Selkirk Yard, Selkirk, NY, discovered GATX 54932, a loaded tank car of Styrene Monomer, Stabilized, dripping product from around the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and SABIC Innovated Plastics, USA, the consignee, and SABIC Petrochemicals Holding USA, the shipper, were notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 20100824-00131). Mike Bethge, CSXT Field Service Hazardous Material Manager, responded and found the bottom outlet valve assembly was not properly secured to the tank car nozzle flange. Three of eight stud nuts where less than tool tight. The stud nuts where tightened to 180 foot pounds of torque, and the leak stopped. The car was staged for two hours and inspected to find no product release. FRA Hazardous Material Inspector John Wurz provided verbal permission to move the car to destination, approximately 0.5 mile away. The car was delivered to the consignee at 16:35 hours. The issue identified was conveyed to SABIC Petrochemicals Holding, USA, Ms. Sharon Moore, 304-863-7764,    This incident did not require a special switching move.    An AAR Q+A 7.1 report will be filed. GATX 54732 was last qualified at Rescar, Inc. Longview, Texas on 07/2010, this was the first trip after re-qualification.    Cause Code: 535  NARRI Code: 5 (3+1+0) x (2+0) = 40
column169: Request that Rescar conduct a spot inspection of the DOT 111A100W1 cars that had BOV Assembley inspections during July re-inspected for less than tool tight stud nuts.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was on the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  Each drum was being weighed.  One of the drums fell from the scale while being weighed and fell onto the drum dolly.  The foot of the drum dolly pierced the drum when it landed on it, spilling approximately one gallon of material onto the dock.  The drum was turned to a position where no further material would leak.  The appropriate personal protective equipment was donned and the spilled material was cleaned up with an absorbent material.  The contents of the broken drum were pumped into a new drum.  The cleanup material and broken drum were placed into a salvage container.  The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The person involved with the incident will verify that each drum is secure on the scale prior to proceeding with the weighing procedures in the future.

column168: On August 10, 2010 at approximately 4:45 PM, Triad dropped a trailer (#3815) at the Veolia West Carrollton facility.  The trailer had 34 drums that were manifested to Veolia’s Pt. Arthur, TX disposal facility on manifest 007457673JJK.  The 34 drums had been rejected by Ross Incineration Services from manifest 006366976JJK.  The original generator of this material was Maryland Sand, Gravel & Stone Site (EPAID# MDD980705164).     While the material handler was securing the trailer with a jack-stand and glad handle at approximately 5:30 PM, they noticed liquid dripping from the trailer.  The material handler immediately notified the supervisor of the leak.  The supervisor pulled the paperwork and determined the leaking material was a Hazardous Waste Liquid that contained PCBs.  The supervisor had the material handler place collection buckets under the trailer to catch any dripping liquid.  The supervisor then notified Veolia EHS Manager, John Hannah and Jim Easter at approximately 6:00 PM.      Upon inspection of the trailer, the supervisor noticed many drums that were leaking, but he could not inspect all the drums without offloading them.  The most suspect drum was a 55-gallon drum that has a clear plastic lid cover on it.  The floor around this drum was saturated with liquids.  Prior to offloading the drums, a double layer of poly-sheeting was placed on dock area and Row 23A.  Approximately 100’ of boom was placed around the poly-sheeting to create a curb to prevent any liquid run-off.  The drums were broken off of the pallets and off-loaded one at a time.  The pallets were very saturated with liquid material.  As the drums were off-loaded, numerous drum lids were replaced because they did not seal.  The offloading of the trailer was completed at approximately at 5:30 AM on August 11, 2010.  The plastic and PPE generated during the offloading were consolidated into three 55-gallon poly drums.
column169: The drums from manifest 007457673JJK were inspected on August 11, 2010 and it was determined that the 55-gallon containers were not DOT shippable for various reasons such as:  1. Some containers did not have UN-Markings  2. Some drums had waste on the exterior of the container  3. Some of the drums were damaged and had questionable integrity    The total number of containers that needed to be overpacked was 31 drums.  The drums were overpacked into new UN-rated 851A2 containers.  All the clean-up material and debris associated with the spill were packaged into six (6) un-rated cubic yard boxes and four (4) un-rated 55-gallon drums.  The clean-up materials were shipped to Veolia's Port Arthur facility on manifest 000488227VES.    Veolia was not the intial shipper or generator of the materials.  Veolia assumed transportion responsibility when the intial transporter transfered contol to Veolia at our West Carrollton, OH facility.  In an attempt to prevent a reoccurance, Veolia notified the generator and the intial transporter of the incident.

Investigation developed that the car had been pulled from the consignees facility prior to completion of unloading.  The consignee had opened the manway cover in preparation for unloading and the train crew pulled the car in error.  The car had been released by the consignee prior to unloading.      Environmental contractor, Hepaco Inc., responded and properly secured the manway cover and cleaned up the spilled material.

column168: Booking: 000320361  CNTR: EMCU3656710   4/P: USBAL/USBAL/PACCT/VELGU  SHP: EVER DIAMOND 0533-097W  ETD: 1700, 8/24/2010  HAZ: 6.1/UN2874  CELL: 091084    1115 AM, 8/24/10    Haz box EMCU3656170 has serious leakage after it was loaded on bay 091084. C/O decided container need to be discharged from Ever Diamond 0533-097 E-W, 1115 AM, 8/24/10.    Since the potential hazards:    1. Toxic: inhalation,ingestion or skin contact with material may cause severe injury or death  2.contact with molten substance may cause severe burns to skin eyes  3. Avoid any ski contact  4. Effects of contact or inhalation may be delayed  5. Fire may produce irritating, corrosive and/or toxic gases  6. Run-off from fire control or dilution water may be corrosive and/or toxic and cause pollution.    1200 PM, 8/24/10    PAC immediately informed MD HAZ Police Department with Seagirt and ERP ( Emergency Response Processing ) Team and Fire Department. They blocked all area and stop all gangs working from noon time.      I was in the terminal around 1200 PM, 8/24. The Capt.of MD Fire Department prohibited any person on board or off board from ship.    1315 PM, 8/24/10    PAC reported to me EMCU3656710 internal package had broken and spread  haz water on ground after it was discharged from ship 1310 PM, 8/24. Since ship worked on midnight started 0001, 8/24. ILA Clerk did not find out leakage until 1100-1115 AM, 8/24, Chief Officer checked all haz cargo position found out leakage on EMCU3657710, cell 091084,  also haz water leaked under container BMOU2118226 , cell 091082.      EMCU3656710 and BMOU2118226 were cut from loading list.    1530 PM, 8/24/10    Emergency HAZ Clearance Team showed up around 1530 PM and cleaned all haz residue around 1730 PM. USCG showed up and checked all leakage area if it has been cleaned out.       1830 PM, 8/24/10    Around 1830, USCG Captain has authorized ship resumed to work from 1900, 8/24.  The ship sailed on 0610, 8/25.  There are 12 hours delay to sail.    1700 PM, 8/24/10    There are two boxes on ground  need to be decontaminated, FSCU 7778430 and FSCU 7744024 before on board.  Haz material spread  on the bottom of two cntrs. MD EPA decided both cntrs need to be completed decontamination procedures before loading on ship.  After clean them on the bottom of two containers, they were loaded to ship.
column169: Shipper need secure all haz cargo when load into container. Properly secure all the time. If single package caused leakage or removable head had problem, they should  apply more strick package with inter/outer packages.

column168: At this date, the accident is still under investigation by the SC Highway Patrol Accident Reconstruction Team and no reports or details have been issued.  This account of the accident may not be factual based on relative information not being available.  Driver was heading south on I77 South out of Charlotte at approx. 2:40PM on August 16th and had just passed the Gold Hill Exit in Ft. Mill, SC when a car pulled over into the right side of our truck causing him to swerve over into the left lanes eventually hitting the concrete median seperating the north and southbound lanes and causing the unit to rollover on on its right side and onto the car that pulled over into him. The unit slid on its right side and caught fire completely destroying the trailer to the point where the only thing left was the rear tandem and the tractor was down to engine and frame only.  The were no identifing marks on the unit so we did not have a positive notification of the incident till around 9PM. The driver and a passenger of the other vehicle were pulled to safety by a passing motorist and were treated and released at a local hospital.  Our Driver suffered a fatal injury during the crash before the unit caught fire.  Most of the product burned but some product did flow into the drainage system under the interstate and into a nearby creek.  Hazardous Materials crews placed underflow dams in the creek to prevent further spread of the material and utilized vacuum truck and absorbant booms and pads to recover the material in the creek. The concrete culverts on the side of the interstate where the material flowed down to the creek caught fire and received extensive damage along with the ajoining woods.  Interstate 77 was closed for approx. 6 hours  before it was reopened to traffic on the southbound side.  A section of pavement approx 80 foot long had to be replaced.  We are working with the SCDOT on their requirements for restoring the general area.  We have also submitted a work plan to the SCDHEC on the environmental work needed. They had some additional requirements and we are awaiting their response to determine the scope of the remaining project.
column169: Continue training on safe driving with a focus of defensive drving skills and techniquesw and crash advoidance.  Make sure Drivers are trained in special-handling characteristics, including high center of gravity,fluid loads subject to surge and effects of surge on braking. Remind Drivers about the effects partial loads have on vehicle stability.  Maintain and review accident crash reports over time to identify potential patterns or trends.  Review drivers MVR annually to make sure drivers are compliant.

column168: THERE WAS A NIAL STICKING OUT OF THE SKID IN FRONT AND IT PUNCTURED THE TOTE DURING TRANSIT BUT DID NOT CAUSE LEAKAGE AT THE TIME BECAUSE THE NAIL WAS PLUGGING THE HOLE. column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading at customer location, a leak occurred from the hose fitting due to a faulty gasket.  Approximately one (1) ounce of free product was released to the catch bucket beneath hose.  Ground surface was not affected, and no cleanup was required.  Consignee handled disposal of free product, along with used/like waste at the facility.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release occurred due to a faulty gasket on the hose fitting, no plans current exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling and procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 08/31/2010 at 18:05 hrs., a private citizen in Bay Minette, AL, contacted Chemtrec to report an odor being emitted from railcar CPDX 582132, a loaded tank car of Molten Sulfur. The car was isolated and the shipper, Chevron Products Corp., local emergency responders and CSXT were notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2010-08-31-00242). Chris Machenberg, a CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager, was dispatched to the scene and found the odor was coming from the pressure relief device (PRD). Upon further inspection, the rupture disk was found to be installed upside down and corroded. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Billy Brunell 228-938-4260. The rupture disk was replaced and the car was released for transport. The CSXT railroad mainline between Mobile, AL and Montgomery, AL was closed by the responding fire department for approximately one hour during this incident.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 439  NARRI Code: 5(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: Chevron performed a Safety Stand Down to discuss the incident with the loaders involved. Hazardous Materials manager Chris Machenberg will be visiting the Chevron facility to meet with and discuss the incident with Chevron personnel.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines Inc driver was delivering gas to a customer location when he noticed fuel leaking from the tank. The driver immediately shut off flow of product but approximately 5 gallons leaked onto concrete. Driver put out spill pads and a boom to prevent product from leaving into soil or drains. SWS first response was called to the scene to verify no product reached drains. This was confirmed by taking samples. All product was cleaned to the satisfaction of all personnel. It was determined that the driver miscalculated the 90% fill and unloaded too much into a tank that is baffled together with another unleaded tank.
column169: FRTL driver will be retrained on unloading procedures, specifically how to calculate proper amounts. Driver will have an incident prevention observation conducted on him prior to returning to normal duties.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering product to a customer location. While unloading the driver miscalcuated the tank capacity. The driver Kevin Jackson was dispatched with 8000 gallons of regular and 1000 gallons of premium.  While dropping the tank's overfill protection cut off the flow of product into tank 1 regular. The driver unlocked the fitting from the ground and let the pressure bleed off and drained the hose. He then tried to put more fuel into the tank, and the overfill flapper stopped the flow again but this time the driver did not have the fitting locked onto the tank. The fitting came off the tank, the driver immediately stopped the flow of product but approximately 30-40 gallons spilled. No fuel reached drains or soil. The oconee county fire dept and Mitch Guthrie of Genesis environmental came to the site. The fuel was cleaned up and Mitch verified that the storm drains had not been contaminated.
column169: The driver will be put through unloading training again. The driver will also have an incident prevention observation conducted on him before being allowed to return to work. The driver will also have a refresher on calculating tank capacities.

column168: On 08/29/2010 at 15:55 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Rose Lake yard in East St. Louis, IL, discovered LTCX 1801, AAR204W, a loaded  tank car of Refrigerated Liquid Argon, leaking from the B-end control box. column168: Upon pulling a pallet containing the product out of the trailer it could be seen there was some spillage on the bottom of the box. The box was loaded on the pallet upside down, and against what the arrows and the box said it should be loaded. The box was flipped over without touching the spilled liquid. The leaking immediately ceased. The box became flimsy from being wet. The plastic bottles were removed from the box. Using rubber gloves the plastic bottlein question's lid was screwed back on and set up right. The bottles appeared to have no residue on them being that they were upside down, and the lid had loosened. The box which had the residue was placed in a plastic bag awaiting hazmat disposal.
column169: Use of better packaging as well as loading procedures should be utilized. Anything containing something as potent as hydrochloric acid should be shipped in something where the lid would not come off with such ease. That part is only a by-product of observing proper loading procedures. If the box had been loaded according to the instructions there would have been no discharge.

column168: Van was parked at Technicians home and a 12-4 Non-Spillable battery was improperly stored and secured in the cargo area of the van that was going back to the office for recycling. Housekeeping in the van was very poor and a piece of material made contact with the terminal causing a small fire.  The technician caught the fire in the incipient stage and successfully extinguished the fire using an 5lb ABC rated extinguisher resulting in minimal damage to the van and truck stock.
column169: Technician was counseled and retrained on the proper storage of batteries while in the cargo area of the van and the need for improved housekeeping.  Company policy requires all return batteries to be secured and protective caps or tape covering both battery terminals.  A safety alert was created and distributed company wide reinforcing this requirement.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While travelling on Interstate 80 westbound near mile marker 187, the Vickery Transportation, Inc. tractor-trailer unit rolled-over.  Apparently the roll-over occurred as a result of the driver falling asleep.  The accident resulted in damage to the tanker, resulting in the release of approximately 3229 gallons of material.  The Ohio State Police, Streetsboro Fire Department, Ohio Department of Transportation and the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency responded to assess the site.  Sunpro, Inc. of North Canton, Ohio was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Sunpro, Inc. utilized a vacuum truck to recover approximately 671 gallons of material from the damaged tanker.  Sunpro, Inc. also utilized the vacuum truck to recover approximately 2843 gallons of material from the impacted ditch line.  The liquid waste was transported to Vickery Environmental, Inc. in Vickery, Ohio for disposal.  Sunpro, Inc. excavated approximately 236.51 tons of contaminated soil over a period of several days.  The solid waste was transported to Waste Management Landfill in Canton, Ohio for disposal. On Tuesday, August 24, 2010, Sunpro, Inc. returned to the site and removed approximately 8261 gallons of waste water from the ditch line, per request of the Ohio Environmental Protection Agency.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Vickery Transportation, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: GATX 200199 was noted by carrier personnel with product odor in area of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.      Shipper representative, SPSI, responded and found the following 3 defects allowing product vapor to escape:    1. Five consecutive pressure plate bolts were found less than tool tight.  The bolts were properly tightened stopping the vapor release from that point.    2. Vapor valve was partially open and the valve plug was less than tool tight.  The valve was closed and the plug removed, retaped and properly installed and tightened stopping the release from the vapor valve.    3. Sample line needle valve was partially open and the valve stem packing nut was loose.  The valve was properly closed and the packing nut tightened stopping the release from the sample line valve.    All three defects were corrected and the car was observed with no further release noted by product odor or instrumentation.     One train crew member was transported to a local medical facility where he was treated and released with no restrictions.  The employee later visited his personal physician and the outcome of that visit is unknown at this time.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: NuStar Savannah Terminal experienced operational issues on the night of August 16, 2010 which resulted in the rail car number HOKX111140 being left pressurized with the unloading hose still connected.  When the operations crew arrived on the morning of August 17th, they thought the rail car had been unloaded and was ready to be moved to another track position. In the process of moving the rail car, the two inch top loading valve was torn off the rail car resulting in a spill of potassium hydroxide. The safety access ramp and tank car unloading arm were damaged as well. After approximately twenty minutes when it was safe to access the top of the rail car, the bleeder valve was opened thereby depressurizing the rail car and stopping the release. An environmental cleanup crew was dispatched and cleanup commenced immediately. An environmental remediation crew was also dispatched. Clean-up and neutralization commenced immediately.
column169: 1. Review and Enhance Procedures and Conduct Training· Terminal Manager will increase his time in the terminal observing day to day activities.   · Review FRA regulations concerning railcar loading, unloading, and preparing for transportation with all employees and document training.  · Formalize procedures for duties of track mobile operator and spotter. Perform and document training with all employees on duties of track mobile operator and spotter.  2. Increase audit of day to day operations to verify policy and procedures are being followed.  · Terminal Management and employees will increase time in the terminal auditing day to day activities.  · Operations Superintendent will perform daily reviews of check list and pass down logs to ensure proper completion.  3. Pass Down Log Review  · Review and improve/modify current pass down log to improve the communications between shift changes.

column168: At approximately 9:30 AM on August 19, 2010, a BKEP Crude driver transporting petroleum crude oil unintentionally left the roadway, traveled across a field and into a small creek.  The driver did not remember leaving the road, and the cause of his condition and the incident is still under investigation.  The driver was removed from the vehicle and ultimately taken to an Oklahoma City hospital for treatment of injuries.                                                                                                 The vehicle and trailer came to rest in the creek bed.  The trailer remained intact and no crude oil was released to the creek.  There was no failure of the crude oil trailer transportation packaging.  Upon impact in the creek bed, the tractor was heavily damaged.  Engine oil and diesel fuel leaked out of the vehicle and entered the water in the creek.  At the time of the incident, there was little to no flow in the creek so the oil was contained in the immediate area of the accident.  A contract response company responded to the incident site and contained and removed all oil using sorbent pads and booms.  A small amount of oil-stained soil was also removed from the site.  In total, we estimate less than 20 gallons of engine oil and fuel were leaked out of the vehicle over a few hours.  The crude oil was pumped out of the tanker and removed from the site. After removal of the crude from the transport, the tractor, trailer and all debris were removed from the site.
column169: It is BKEP's belief that vehicle accidents occur as a result of 1) equipment failure, 2) driver error/behavior issue, or 3)driver medical condition/issue.  At this time, we have eliminated equipment failure as the cause of the accident.  Therefore, we believe that the accident was caused by driver error, driver medical condition, or combination of the two.  Due to the nature and extent of his injuries, we have not been able to conduct a thorough and complete interview with the driver nor have we obtained a complete record of his doctor's medical findings.  This information is necessary to determine the cause of the accident. We are working to gather this information from the driver and his doctor to better understand what happened to the employee immediately before he lost control of the vehicle (i.e.,medically), and understand how these conditions may have contributed to the accident.  We are also evaluating other potential contributing factors such as prescription medications taken by the driver.  Our Trucking Operations Manager will be gathering this information from the driver and his doctor to review with our internal Incident Investigation Team, and we will provide an update to you as the root cause of the accident and appropriate corrective measures to prevent reoccurrence are developed more clearly.  We expect this information will be collected within the next two to three weeks, and an update can be provided soon thereafter.
