column168: Contaminated soil is brought to the transload facility in dump trucks and directly transloaded into lined gondola railcars.  The railcar liners is a woven fabric with a polymer applied on inside and outside of the liner during manufacturing.  The installed liner covers all interior surfaces of the railcar for the transloading operations. The liners closed and secured after transloading to fully cover and enclose the transloaded soils for rail shipment.    After transloading and closing the liners it was observed that an unidentified liquid was leaking from drip holes on the bottom of several railcars.  When this drippage was discovered buckets were placed to collect the liquid for proper disposal.  Absorbants were added to the collected liquids.    In total 32 manifested truck loads were transloaded into a total of 8 railcars during the two day period of August 23 and 24.  All 8 railcars developed the weepage of liquids within 2 days of being loaded.  The 8 original railcars were transloaded into a second set of 8 railcars with two liners between August 28 and September 1.  5 of the 'new' railcars developed similar weepage of liquids beginning on September 3.  Product from these 5 railcars was again transloaded into other railcars with 3 liners and 4,000# of absorbant mixed into the soils during transloading.  The second transloading of the soils was performed between September 10 and 16.  No weepage of liquids has been observed from the railcars transloaded between Sept 10 and 16.     The cause of liquids being released by the manifested solid soils has not been determined.
column169: Actions are being taken by the generator of the soils to modify the soils adequately to contain no flowable liquids before truck shipment to the truck to rail transload facilty

column168: It was originally reported that a material may have leaked from the trailer.  Once TMC Services personnel arrived on site and confirmed a release, the CTDEP and local FD was notified of the release.      TMC personnel began offloading the drums from the trailer to determine which drums had leaked.  Once the damaged drums had been located they were overpacked and cleanup activities of the released materials commenced.  All released materials were collected and containerized for transportation and disposal activities.      Ms. Roseanne Shavolta (860-982-7066) of CTDEP was on site providing oversight of the response/cleanup activities.

Two (2) 260 gallon IBC of Fyfanon ULV (malathion) were being delivered to an aerial applicator. When the driver of the delivery vehicle made the turn from Old Highway 90 to CR411, the totes shifted backward and broke through the closed endgates on the vehicle. One IBC ruptured spilling its entire contents onto the road surface and into the roadside ditch: the second IBC was damaged but only lost approximately 10% of its contents, also in the roadside ditch. An emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene. Initial efforts were made to recover any free liquids however, most of the liquids had soaked into the soil. The road surface was cleaned and ditch excavated to remove all impacted soils. Excavated soils will be profiled and disposed of in an approved landfill. The remaining liquid in the damaged tote was transferred to another empty IBC tote with the same UN specification and then transported onto its intended destination.
column169: Additional training on proper load securement procedures when transporting IBCs was provided at the shipping facility.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  After completion of off-loading at the consignee's location the tanker failed due to operator error.  Apparently the driver failed to open a vent on the tanker, causing a vacuum effect, which resulted in the tanker cracking.  Approximately 80 gallons of free product were released and impacted asphalt and a nearby storm drain.  SET Environmental, Inc. of Houston, Texas was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  SET Environmental, Inc. inspected the impacted storm drain and discovered that the outfall of the storm drain is in a bayou approximately 3/4 of a mile away.  SET Environmental, Inc. inspected the bayou and discovered no evidence that the product reached the bayou.  Due to the nature of the product, it was determined that no further cleanup was necessary.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Basic Chemical Solutions, LLC will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.    Basic Chemical Solutions, LLC will also evaluate trailer configuration and operation.

At 22:15 dock worker Ralph Romo was moving dunnage (plywood) at the beginning of this shift. A piece of plywoodslid from the stack and punctured a small 1/2 inch hole in the plastic tote about 4 inches from the bottom of the tote.Ralph notified me immediately and together we were able to put tape over the hole and stop the leak. 2 gallons hadleaked from the tote by the time we got the leak to stop. I then called Chemtrec and Conway Safety to initiate thechemical incident report and gather further instructions. I was told to keep all paper and wood away from the spilland that a team was coming from OSI in Merrillville IN to handle the clean up.We isolated the tote and placed oil dry around the spill to contain the seepage.OSI arrived about 2:30 and placed the material into 5 containment drums and cleaned up the spill. OSI was here inLaSalleuntil3:15.Approximately 4 gallon had spilled from the tote by the time the clean up was completed. All oil dry was contained ina separate containment drum.
column169: *Isolate all Haz-mat on the dock and block with dunnage. Retrain Ralph Romo on forklift operations. Use extremecaution around all Haz-mat materials.

INITIAL INSPECTION MADE IT EVIDENT THAT THE BOX CONTAINED A CORROSIVE MATERIAL AND SINCE THE SHIPPING PAPERS WERE CLEARLY DISPLAYED ON TOP, I WAS ABLE TO READ THE CONTENTS AS A SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. column168: This shipment was questioned because the air waybill description said sample of fragrances. The shipment was opened and it contained perfume. A Material Safety Data Sheet on the product listed the flash point as UN 1266, Perfumery Products,class 3, Packing Group III. Since the shipper did not offer the shipment with any dangerous goods markings, DG labeling, nor with a Shipper's Declaration for Dangerous Goods it is believed to be undeclared DG. FAA agent Juni Abbot was notified and the shipment was held pending FAA investigation.

column168: Approximately 0400 on Aug 28, 2010 a backpack belonging to a jumpseating crewmemeber caught on fire in the galley of a B757, Flight #1487.  The aircraft was loaded but had not left the gate when the incident occured.  The backpack had a M3Combat flashlight made by Surefire.  The 3 batteries inside were CR123A made by Great Power Battery Co. Guangzhou, China.  One of the batteries exhibited signs of thermal runaway causing the fire.  The FedEx fire department put out the fire and the backpack was moved to the Flight Safey office for investigation.  No injuries occured.  NTSB, National Response Center (#952525) and local FAA agent were notified.  A voice mail was left for Janet McLaughlin in FAA HQ in Washington.

column168: Driver was exiting I-65 North at mile marker 22 in Tennessee.  Exit ramp is of a clover leaf design.  Tractor and tank left continued straight through the curve of the exit ramp, continued across an open grassy area, and then crossed over the adjacent northbound entrance ramp to I-65 North where tractor and tank struck Ford explorer traveling on entrance ramp.  Both vehicles came to rest along side of north bound entrance ramp against embankment.  Collision resulted in tank disconnecting from tractor.  Tank was ruptured by tractor when it disconnected causing hole in lower portion of tank approximately 5 inches in diameter.  Product leaked until it was below the hole.  Product was naturally contained below the tank in a ditch.  Product stayed contained due to ditch sloping inward toward and under the tanker.  There was no release to a water supply or onto the road.  Product stayed contained within a 100 foot are.  Response crew contained product to the crash scene and pumped approximately 23,000 pounds from the ground into another tanker.  Another approximate 7,000 pounds was pumped from damaged tanker into another tanker. That left approximately 18,000 that was waste hauled.  The crash took place at 0716 hours in the morning and all product but approximately 4,000 pounds was cleaned up at 2300 hours that night.  Area was cordoned off and the remaining approximate 4,000 punds was cleane up the next morning before 1000 hours.  Some earth was damaged and required two dump trucks of top soil and hay and seed.
column169: The driver was hired 08/23/2010 and the accident occurred 08/23/2010.  Therefore, he had been driving for Nelson Brothers, LLC for less than seven days.  This was his second dispatch.  He had already made one run on a similar route.  In investigating the accident, the driver made the statement that he "messed up" by not realizing he was that far in to the turn when he looked back to his co-driver to tell him to wake up to change out.  And, at that point it was too late, as he states, to try to stay in the curve so he rode it out straight through the curve and tried to control the tractor and trailer instead of taking the chance of rolling it.  We can use this incident and how it happened for future training of drivers.  We are scheduling an accident re-construction and will evaluate other prevention action items once it is complete.  The driver was terminated from employment with Nelson Brothers, LLC for being at fault.

column168: Employee was on his route when he noticed a strong odor after opening his trailer door.  Employee attempted to investigate, but could not go far into the trailer because of the odor.  The employee contacted his supervisor who contacted the safety department.  Since a shipment of poison product (UN2995) was on the trailer, the safety department contacted a spill response vendor to determine what had spilled, as well as to clean it up.  The spill response vendor found a carton of product (UN2995) that contained a leaking container.  They cleaned the spill on the trailer floor, then cleaned the floor itself. THE CARGO CONTENTS (I.E. COMPRESSED AND LIQUEFIELD ATMOSPHERIC, FLAMMABLE AND NON-FLAMMABLE GASES) OF THE VEHICLE IN THE CARGO BOX (8'x20 ENCLOSED VAN BODY) WERE RELEASED FROM THE CARGO HOLD. THE OVERTURN OF THE VEHICLE CAUSED THE CONTENTS OF (2) LIQUID OXYGEN CYLINDER (4500 CU FT, EA.) TO VENT TO THE ATMOSPHERE THRU THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE ON THE CYLINDERS AND THE CONTENTS OF (1) ACETYLENE CYLIND (40 CU FT) TO BE RELEASED DUE TO PHYSICAL DAMAGE TO THE VALVE. column168: During unloading of the tank truck, approsimately 20 gallons of diesel fuel was spill onto the area surrounding the diesel fuel receiving tanks outside the containment area.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to remove petroleum contaminated soil.  The impacted soil was containerized for transportation and proper disposal.  The area was back filled with native materials and compacted.

Once the tractor had left the roadway, the local authorities had arrived on site and dispatched Marshall Miller and Associates for initial containment activities.  An estimated 25 gallons of UN1263 paint was released from the lid of the unit and affected soils beneath the overturned tractor and tanker.  No storm drains or surface waters were impacted by the release.     Following the removal of the driver from his cab, transfer activities commenced from the overturned tanker and into a rescue tanker.  The transfer concluded without any additional release and all personnel the left the site once the damaged vehicle had been removed from the site.      The contractor then returned with excavation equipment to remove the impacted soils.

column168: THE TANK IS A REAR UNLOADER WITH THE DOME COVER AT THE REAR OF THE TANK. THE UNLOADING AREA AT THE CONSIGNEE IS ON A DOWNWARD SLOPE WITH THE REAR OF THE TANK FACING DOWN THE SLOPE. THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE, HOOKED UP HIS HOSES, AND PRESSURIZED THE TANK PRIOR TO UNLOADING. HE THEN SHUT OFF HIS COMPRESSOR WHILE WAITING FOR SOMEONE TO COME OUT AND SIGN HIS PAPER WORK. HOWEVER, HE FAILED TO CLOSE THE BALL VALVES ON THE XMAS TREE AND ON THE COMPRESSOR PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. AN EMPLOYEE OF THE CONSIGNEE CAME OUT AND SIGNED THE DRIVERS PAPERWORK. THE DRIVER THEN STARTED HIS COMPRESSOR. WHEN HE DID SO, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE BEGAN TO VENT A MIST OF ACID. EVIDENTLY WITH THE COMPRESSOR OFF AND THE BALL VALVES OPEN ACID HAD BLED BACK THROUGH THE AIR LINE TO THE COMPRESSOR. BOTH THE EMPLOYEE AND THE DRIVER WEE TAKEN TO SUBURBAN HOSPITAL IN BETHESDA MD WHERE THEY WERE TREATED FOR SUPERFICIAL INJURIES AND RELEASED.
column169: DRIVER SUSPENED FROM WORK. HE WAS COUNSELED AND RETRAINED ON PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES AND TECHNIQUES.

column168: COASTAL DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING EAST ON HWY 90 IN A FLATBED TRUCK WHEN HE NOTICED A LEAK FROM ONE OF THIS TOTES. HE PULLEED OVER TO THE SHOLDER AND CONTACTED HIS SUPEREVISOR. UPONDISCOVERY OF THE LEAK BY AN EMPLOYEE AT 1:00 PM, THE APPROPRIATE STATE AGENCIES AND SPILL CONTRACTOR WERE CONTACTED. AN EMPTY TOTE WAS BROUGT TO THE SITE WHERE THE TRUCK WITH THE LEAKING TOTE WAS PARKED AND THE REMAINING MATEIAL WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE LEAKING TOTE TO THE EMPTY TOTE. THE SPILL CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION AT 4:30 PM AND BEGAN DECONTAMINATING THE TOTE, THE TRAILER AND OTHER TOTES REMAINING ON THE TRUCK. THEY ALSO REMOVED CONTAMINATED SOIL NEAR THE TRUCK.
column169: ALL TOTES ARE TESTED AS PRESCRIBED BY D.O.T. THE TOTE THAT LEAKED WAS TESTED IN SEPTEMBER 2009 AND WAS CERTIFIED FOR 30 MONTHS FROM THAT DATE. THE TOTE WAS INSPECTED BEFORE IT WAS FILLED AND BY THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK-NO LEAK WAS OBSERVED. PRESUMABLY, THE TOTE CRACKED WHILE IN TRANSIT. COASTAL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT TANKS AS PRESCRIBED BY D.O.T. BEFORE FILLING AND LOADING.

column168: Driver was testing meter on his own, by himself, against company regulations, to be sure that the numbers on the meter were turning like they should. He had put the nozzle into one of the truck’s compartments, started pumping, climbed down off of the truck to check meter. Before he could get back up on the truck, the nozzle turned sideways, fell onto the ground and pumped 23 gallons of fuel on to the asphalt pavement before stopped. There were no drains around and all fuel stayed on the asphalt until emergency response cleaned it up. Asphalt has since been replaced.
column169: Company has procedures for drivers and an environmentally safe concrete pad or any testing like this to be done. Driver violated our company polices and was terminated. All other employees have been re-schooled in company policies and procedures.

column168: A VEHICLE OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. HAD ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION A SHIPMENT OF MINE TAILINGS DESTINED FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  WHILE EN ROUTE, THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO TAKE EVASIVE ACTIONS TO AVOID IMPACTING OTHER VEHICLES THAT WERE ATTEMPTING TO AVOID A VEHICLE OPERATING IN AN ERRATIC FASHION.  THE EVASIVE ACTION TAKEN BY THE CLEAN HARBOR'S DRIVER RESULTING IN THE VEHICLE VEERING ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY WHICH WAS APPROXIMATELY THREE FEET IN WIDTH LEADING TO A STEEP EMBANKMENT.  THE FORWARD MOMEMTUM OF THE VEHICLE CAUSED THE UNIT TO SLIDE OFF THE ROADWAY AND DOWN THE EMBANKMENT.  THIS ACTION CAUSED THE DUMP TRAILER TO ROLL ONTO ITS SIDE ALLOWING THE MAJORITY OF ITS LADING TO SPILL ONTO A GRASS-COVERED MEADOW.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THE TRACTOR DID NOT  ROLL-OVER AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.                                                          WITNESSES TO THE ACCIDENT CONTACTED EMERGENCY SERVICES WHO, UPON ARRIVAL, SECURED THE ACCIDENT SCENE AND SECURED MEDICAL ATTENTION FOR THE DRIVER.  THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO A LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITY WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FOR MINOR INJURIES SUSTAINED AS A RESULT OF THE CRASH.  A REPORT OF THE RELEASE WAS MADE TO CLEAN HARBORS  WHICH IN TURN RESULTED IN THE ACTIVATION OF CLEAN HARBOR'S INTERNAL CRISIS MANAGEMENT TEAM.  IT WAS AT THIS TIME THAT CLEAN HARBORS CONTACTED BOTH THE COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC HEALTH AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  INTERNAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE ALSO MADE IN ORDER TO INITIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITIES WHICH INCLUDED DISPATCH OF A PROJECT MANAGER AND A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO SECURE THE AREA IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE.  IN ADDITION, THE SHIPPER OF THE MATERIAL WAS NOTIFIED TO ALERT THEM OF THE INCIDENT.                UPON ARRIVAL OF CLEAN HARBOR'S PROJECT MANAGER, A MEETING WAS HELD WITH ON-SCENE LAW ENFORCEMENT AND EMERGENCY  SERVICE.  DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE MATERIAL INVOLVED, THE FACT THAT IT POSED NO REAL AND/OR IMMINENT THREAT TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC OR THE ENVIRONMENT, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO SECURE THE SPILL SCENE AND INITIATE CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES DURING DAYLIGHT   HOURS.  ALL PARTIES AGREED AND AT FIRST LIGHT CLEAN-UP AND REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES COMMENCED WHICH INCLUDED THE CONTAINERIZATION OF THE SPILL MATERIAL INTO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE, EXCAVATION AND CONTAINERIZATION OF ALL IMPACTED SOIL,0  TRANSPORTATION AND DISPOSAL OF THE ORIGINAL SHIPMENT AS WELL AS ALL SPILL DEBRIS GENERATED DURING THE RESPONSE ACTIVITIES REMOVAL OF THE DAMAGED VEHICLES AND SITE RESTORATION ACTIVITIES.  ONCE COMPLETED, ALL EQUIPMENT AND SUPPLIES USED  THROUGHOUT THE RESPONSE ACTION WERE DEMOBILIZED AND CLEAN HARBORS DEPARTED THE SCENE.    *THERE WAS NO TON SETTING FOR RAM....THIS WAS 10 TONS*
column169: It is the belief of Clean Harbors that the events that lead up to the accident was not preventable by Clean Harbor's driver. In fact, it is our beliefthat the driver, in electing to steer into the soft shoulder took those steps necessary to safeguard the well being of other citizens operating on thepublic roadway. In doing so, he placed his own safety in jeopardy. If he had not taken the evasive action he chose, other vehicles and individualswould have been placed in harms way. As a result of our internal investigation, though while this accident resulted in a significant monetary loss,the driver's actions potentially saved lives.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: While traveling to a customer delivery location, the bulk truck (CTMV) cargo tank was driven under a train trestle.  The relief valves in the top of the tank made contact with an overhead steel girder, shearing the top off of both relief valves and damaging the relief valve opening on the rear of the tank.  The vehicle was stopped a short distance afterward, where fire responders provided a dispersing water spray until the cargo tank vapor release was mitigated.  The remainder of the propane in the cargo tank was safely dispersed at a nearby trash dump under the auspices of emergency personnel.

column168: On 8-19-10 approx 3:30 NMex time, the Hobbs office was notified by Key Energy dispatch office that one of our vehicles had been in a roll-over on HWY 529 between mile marker 4-5. Jaime Pacheco took the call and informed me (Ken) of the accident. I went to the sight and upon arrival saw the truck turned over laying in the north barrow ditch. Armando, the driver, was in the Key truck with the DPS officer and was in good condition with no cut or scrapes. Had refused to go to the Hobbs hospital but had been checked out by the Ambulance service and later had told me he had blacked out so I told him he needed to go to a hospital and get checked out for sure incase of any internal damage. Danny Williams the RSS Salesman was also at the sight and I had asked him to take Armando to Artesia Hospital and also wait with him until his release and until our safety man Charlie Bishop arrive to drug test him. He came Out with a clean bill of health and was given some pain meds for bumps and post accident aches.   Meanwhile at the accident sight we looked over everything while waiting for other emergency crews to arrive that the NMHP had called. The transport tanker was laying on its side and was leaking acid out of the front compartment hatch, about a pencil thick stream. The truck had 1000 gal acid a 90/10 blend with xylene. NMHP had called the Hazardous Response team to the sight and about this time the Fire Chief showed up on location and was put in charge. I was told to find a company to suck   the acid from the truck which we contacted Macklasky (SP) who showed up about 5:00pm. The Haz-mat clew showed up about 30mm prior. An evaluation from the Haz-mat team was made and a plan was devised. From this point on the Haz-mat team looked as if they didnt have a clue the rest of the night.
column169: DRIVERS WILL GO THROUGH AN ADDITIONAL DEFENSIVE DRIVING CLASS AND WE WILL STRESS AGAIN THE IMPORTANCE OF PAYING ATTENTION AT ALL TIMES WHEN DRIVING.

ALL OF THE CONTAMINATION WAS REMOVED.
column169: WITH THE EXCEPTION OF DEATH THIS WAS AS BAD AS IT COULD BE. JOHN WAS VERY CLOSE TO DEATH THOUGH AND IT WAS ALL CAUSED BY ONE INDIVIDUAL. THIS INDIVIDUAL HAD NO INSURANCE AND NO RESPONSIBILITY. NOTHING COULD HAVE BEEN DONE TO PREVENT THIS ACCIDENT OTHER THAN MAYBE TO REQUIRE PERSONAL VEHICLES TO MEET THE SAME SAFETY CRITERIA THAT COMMERCIAL VEHICLES DO.

column168: A transfer hose connecting a tube trailer to a customer supply system ruptured and released gaseous hydrogen that ignited explosively. The contents of the trailer were consumed in the ensuring fire that was allowed to “burn off” the hydrogen remaining in the trailer.   The incident involved hose rupture connecting a trailer at a customer site that is used to maintain a continuous supply to a customer. Continuous supply is maintained by having one trailer connected as a supply source while the second trailer is being refilled. During the delivery of a refilled trailer to the customer, the refilled trailer is connected to a customer prior to isolating and disconnecting the trailer that is in service at the customer.   In this incident, the refilled trailer had just been connected to the customer pressure reducing station and the second trailer was in the process of being disconnected for return and refilling. While disconnecting the second trailer the driver heard an unusual sound from the direction of the recently connected trailer. Before he was able to investigate the source of the sound, there was an explosive ignition followed by a fire.   There was no breach of any of the cylinders comprising the tube trailer, nor did the rupture discs on any of the manifolded tubes function during the ensuing fire. The hose was not equipped with excess flow devices and, as a result, non-metallic components of hose were consumed in the fire. Because the hose was consumed, a root cause for the incident cannot be accurately determined.
